Critical Issues

These must be resolved before Phase 6 ships any feature that depends on content.

---
1. Create routes are completely unprotected

File: routes/index.tsx:102–125

The entire /content route tree has no RoleGate or PermissionGate wrapping it:

{
  path: 'content',
  element: <Outlet />,   // ← no guard
  children: [
    { path: 'rooms/create', element: <RoomCreatePage /> },
    { path: 'courses/create', element: <CourseCreatePage /> },
    { path: 'problems/create', element: <ProblemCreatePage /> },

Any authenticated user — including students — can navigate directly to /content/rooms/create, see the full authoring form, and submit. The page hides the "New Room" button via usePermissions('publish:content') but only when arriving via the list page. Direct URL access bypasses this entirely. The backend will reject the request, but students get a confusing authoring UI.

---
2. The "Edit" button in RoomDetailPage navigates to a 404

File: pages/content/rooms/RoomDetailPage.tsx:97

onClick={() => navigate(`/content/rooms/${room.slug}/edit`)}

The route rooms/:slug/edit does not exist in the router. There is no RoomEditPage and no registered route. Clicking "Edit" on any draft room produces a Not Found screen. This is the primary authoring workflow for content managers.

---
3. Search fires a POST request on every character — no debounce

File: pages/content/search/SearchPage.tsx:80, 103–108

const { data, isFetching, isError } = useContentSearch(query, kind)
// ...
onChange={(e) => setQuery(e.target.value)}

useContentSearch has enabled: q.trim().length >= 2. Once the query reaches 2 characters, every subsequent keystroke fires POST /api/v1/search immediately. Typing "data structures" generates 13 API calls. The useDebouncedSearch hook in useContentSearch.ts exists but is never used anywhere. The SearchPage imports and uses the non-debounced version.

---
4. RoomBody uses array index as React key

File: components/content/BlockRenderer.tsx:177

{blocks.map((block, i) => (
  <BlockRenderer key={i} block={block} />
))}

Index keys cause React to reuse the wrong DOM node when blocks are removed from the middle or reordered. In the BlockEditor (which allows remove-by-index), this causes controlled <input> and <Textarea> values to display in the wrong block after a deletion. The blocks have no stable id field, so the fix requires either adding id to block types or using a stable hash of the block's position and type as the key.

---
5. Hooks called with empty-string IDs before data resolves

Files:
- pages/content/rooms/RoomDetailPage.tsx:38–41 — useRoomLifecycle(room?.id ?? '', slug ?? '')
- pages/content/problems/ProblemDetailPage.tsx:23–26 — usePublishProblem(problem?.id ?? '', slug ?? '')
- pages/content/courses/CourseDetailPage.tsx:20 — useRemoveRoomFromCourse(course?.id ?? '')

Each hook closes over an empty string '' during the initial render when data hasn't loaded yet. The mutation functions returned by these hooks reference that empty ID at the time the hook was called, not reactively. If the mutation somehow fires before the data query resolves (e.g., via a race condition or direct test call), it makes a request to /rooms//approve or /courses//rooms/x, producing a malformed URL that goes to an unintended backend handler.

---
6. ProblemCreatePage test case failures leave orphaned partial problems

File: pages/content/problems/ProblemCreatePage.tsx:65–76

const problem = await createProblem(...)
for (const tc of testCases.filter(...)) {
  await contentService.addTestCase(problem.id, tc)  // no try/catch
}
toast.success(...)
navigate(...)

If createProblem succeeds but any subsequent addTestCase call throws (network error, validation failure), the problem exists in the database with zero or partial test cases, but the catch in onSubmit catches the error at the for loop level and shows "Failed to create problem." This leaves the user on the create page believing nothing was created, when in fact an unpublished draft problem now exists. There is also no per-test-case error reporting — a partial failure produces the same error message as a total failure.

