14. Problem statement rendered as raw text, not Markdown

File: pages/content/problems/ProblemDetailPage.tsx

<pre className="whitespace-pre-wrap text-sm leading-relaxed font-sans">
  {problem.statementMd}
</pre>

The product documentation specifies statementMd as Markdown. Rendering it inside a <pre> shows raw markdown syntax (**bold**, - bullets, $math$) as literal text. This makes the statement unreadable for problems with any formatting. At minimum, a Markdown-to-HTML renderer is needed here. Until one is added, the field name statementMd is misleading to users who expect rendered output.

---
15. useRoomLifecycle invalidate function closes over a stale invalidate reference

File: hooks/useRooms.ts:56–77

const invalidate = () => {
  qc.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: [...QUERY_KEYS.ROOMS, slug] })
  qc.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: QUERY_KEYS.ROOMS })
}

invalidate is a plain function defined inside the hook body. Each time useRoomLifecycle renders, invalidate is redefined. Each useMutation captures the invalidate reference at the time the mutation is created. If the hook re-renders between when a mutation object is created and when the mutation resolves, the onSuccess handler may fire with a stale invalidate closure. The fix is useCallback(() => {...}, [qc, slug]).

---
16. Query cache inconsistency after room lifecycle actions

File: hooks/useRooms.ts:49

useUpdateRoom calls:
qc.setQueryData([...QUERY_KEYS.ROOMS, room.slug], room)

But useRoom queries by slug using key [...QUERY_KEYS.ROOMS, slug]. After an update, setQueryData correctly updates the detail cache. However, after lifecycle actions (submitForReview, approve, etc.), the cache is invalidated rather than updated — triggering a network refetch. This is correct behavior, but it means a brief loading flash after every lifecycle action. This is a UX gap compared to phases 1-4, where mutations used setQueryData for instant optimistic updates.

